{{summary1}}

I need you to write queries for a neural search from the web.  Your role is to provide the reader of the summary with additional sources to understand a concept. 
You will use exa to make searches. 

Exa uses a transformer architecture to predict links given text, and it gets its power from having been trained on the way that people talk about links on the Internet. This training produces a model that returns links that are both high in relevance and quality. However, the model does expect queries that look like how people describe a link on the Internet. For example, 'best restaurants in SF" is a bad query, whereas "Here is the best restaurant in SF:" is a good query.

Since your summary is focused on helping students revise their course content for their exam, focus on the concepts that are difficult to understand, and write searches with keywords helping the user understand. Focus on: blog posts, articles, videos, and PDFs.
Tips and tricks:

1. When possible, try to avoid keyword searches.

The results tend to be less robust and useful, because they look very different from the type of ways people might talk about links on the internet. Instead of “demand curve” try something like “Here is an easy to understand blog post explaining the demand curve:”

2. Rephrase questions to look more like answers.

Questions tend to be bad prompts because people sharing links on the internet don’t usually precede links with questions. If you add "I found a good answer here:" after the question the results are often better.

For example, instead of searching for “What’s the best resource to understand the use of the four Ps in marketing?”, try rephrase the question to resemble an answer;

“This is the best resource on how to get understand the role of the four Ps in Marketing”

3. Use modifiers to control the type of results returned: Do not hesitate to write adjectives that define what a reader would need in educational content to understand a concept. Use for instance comprehensive, simplified, interactive, advanced or concise depending on the concept. Of course, use other adjectives if they fit better. 

4. Use semi colons at the end of the queries

5: Separate each query by ";" and write  5 queries all separated by ;

MAKE SURE TO INSERT ";" BETWEEN EACH QUERY
